Testing Strategy for "Flights from Chicago" Functionality

Selected Area: Search

The search function is a crucial part of the "Flights from Chicago" functionality, allowing users to find and select flights based on their preferences and needs. 
Here is a testing strategy and some test cases that can be executed to validate the functionality of the search box on the page:

Test Planning:
Understand the requirements and functionalities of the "Flights from Chicago" page.
Identify test scenarios and prioritize them based on their criticality and impact on user experience.
Define test objectives, scope, resources, and timelines.
Create a test plan document outlining the testing approach, methodologies, and responsibilities.

Functional Testing:
Perform functional testing to ensure that all features on the page work as expected.
Test scenarios include searching for flights, viewing daily fares, accessing information panels, and browsing popular deals.

Regression Testing:
Execute regression tests to ensure that recent changes or updates haven't introduced new defects or affected existing functionalities.
Automate regression tests wherever possible to speed up the testing process and ensure consistency.

User Interface Testing:
Validate the user interface elements such as buttons, links, forms, and navigation menus for correctness, consistency, and responsiveness across different devices and screen sizes.

Performance Testing:
Conduct performance testing to assess the responsiveness, scalability, and stability of the website under various load conditions.
Measure page load times, server response times, and transaction throughput to identify potential performance bottlenecks.

Security Testing:
Perform security testing to identify and address vulnerabilities such as cross-site scripting (XSS), SQL injection, and sensitive data exposure.
Ensure that user data is encrypted, authentication mechanisms are robust, and access controls are properly implemented.

Accessibility Testing:
Evaluate the accessibility of the website to ensure that it complies with accessibility standards such as WCAG (Web Content Accessibility Guidelines).
Test for keyboard navigation, screen reader compatibility, and color contrast for users with disabilities.

Compatibility Testing:
Test the website across different browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge) and versions to ensure consistent behavior and rendering.
Verify compatibility with various operating systems (Windows, macOS, Linux) and devices (desktops, laptops, tablets, smartphones).

Localization Testing:
Validate the website's functionality, content, and language support for different regions and locales.
Test for proper translation, date/time formats, currency symbols, and cultural sensitivities.

